      <h1>Strategic Prevention Framework</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        SAMHSA's five-step planning process used by U.S. communities — assessment,
        capacity, planning, implementation, evaluation — and how prevention
        professionals apply it to problem gambling.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>What the SPF is</h2>
      <p>
        The Strategic Prevention Framework (SPF) is a five-step planning process
        developed by the Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration
        (SAMHSA) and its Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP). SAMHSA
        describes it as a comprehensive guide that prevention professionals use to
        plan, implement, and evaluate prevention practices and programs (SAMHSA, <em>A
        Guide to SAMHSA's Strategic Prevention Framework</em>, PEP19-01, 2019). It was
        built to help states, tribes, communities, and coalitions address
        substance misuse and related behavioral-health problems using local data
        rather than assumption.
      </p>
      <p>
        The five steps are <strong>Assessment</strong>, <strong>Capacity</strong>,
        <strong>Planning</strong>, <strong>Implementation</strong>, and
        <strong>Evaluation</strong>, with two cross-cutting principles —
        <strong>cultural competence</strong> and <strong>sustainability</strong> —
        woven through every step (SAMHSA, SPTAC, n.d.). Two features matter most
        for practitioners. First, the SPF is <strong>data-driven</strong>: each
        step gathers and uses data to inform the next, so decisions about what
        to do and whom to reach are grounded in documented need. Second, it is
        <strong>iterative</strong>, not linear — usually drawn as a circle.
        Evaluation findings feed back into assessment, capacity, and planning,
        so communities refine their approach across cycles instead of treating
        prevention as a one-time project.
      </p>

      <h3>Why a substance-misuse framework applies to problem gambling</h3>
      <p>
        The SPF was built for substance prevention, and most of the training
        examples in the field still come from alcohol, cannabis, and prescription
        drugs. It transfers to gambling because the SPF is a <em>planning
        process</em>, not a substance-specific curriculum. Its logic — find out
        where the problem is, build the capacity to act, plan around local risk
        and protective factors, deliver evidence-based interventions with
        fidelity, and evaluate — is agnostic to the behavioral-health problem
        being addressed.
      </p>
      <p>
        The field has acted on that. The National Council on Problem Gambling
        (NCPG) tells applicants to its national Agility Grants program — the
        first nationwide grant program dedicated to problem gambling prevention
        — that they are strongly encouraged to review the SAMHSA SPF before
        submitting (NCPG, Agility Grants, 2026). Education Development Center
        (EDC) offers a workshop, <em>Implementing the Strategic Prevention
        Framework to Prevent Problem Gambling</em>, that walks state and
        community prevention practitioners through applying the SPF's
        assessment, capacity, and planning steps specifically to gambling (EDC,
        2026). In short, the SPF is the organizing spine the gambling
        prevention field has adopted from substance prevention — eyes open
        about where the fit needs work.
      </p>
      <p>
        A note on scope and language throughout this page: gambling harm exists
        on a continuum, from no harm through at-risk play to gambling disorder,
        and prevention addresses that whole spectrum. The SPF distinguishes
        prevention work (reducing harm before or early in its development)
        from treatment; NCPG draws the same line, framing prevention as work
        directed at people who have not yet gambled or whose gambling is
        limited (NCPG, Agility Grants, 2026).
      </p>

      <h2>The five SPF steps, applied to problem gambling</h2>

      <h3>Step 1 — Assessment</h3>
      <p>
        Assessment answers <em>"What is the problem, and where and to whom is
        it happening?"</em> (SAMHSA, PEP19-01, 2019). A complete assessment
        looks at the consumption and consequence patterns of the behavior, the
        risk and protective factors that drive it, and the community's own
        resources and readiness to respond. The Community Tool Box frames this
        as understanding the community, collecting information about the
        problem, analyzing it, and identifying community assets — using public
        records, surveys, focus groups, key-informant interviews, and tools
        such as SWOT analysis (KU Center for Community Health &amp;
        Development, Community Tool Box, Chapter 3, 1994–2025).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The gambling application — and the data challenge.</strong>
        Gambling surveillance is thinner than substance surveillance. For
        substances, practitioners can pull state and local estimates from
        established systems — the Youth Risk Behavior Surveillance System, the
        National Survey on Drug Use and Health, state youth surveys, and
        treatment-admission and overdose data. Gambling rarely has an
        equivalent ongoing, geographically granular stream. The most
        authoritative national picture is NCPG's periodic National Survey on
        Gambling Attitudes and Gambling Experiences (NGAGE), conducted in
        2018, 2021, and 2024 — and NCPG is explicit that NGAGE is not a
        prevalence study of gambling addiction but a measure of attitudes,
        experiences, and behaviors (NCPG, NGAGE 3.0, 2024). NGAGE 3.0 found
        that about 8% of American adults — roughly 20 million people —
        reported at least one indicator of problematic gambling behavior
        "many times" in the past year, and identified the greatest risk
        predictors as participating in many different gambling activities,
        gambling weekly or more often, believing gambling is a good way to
        make money, betting on sports or fantasy sports, gambling online, and
        being male and/or under age 35 (NCPG, NGAGE 3.0, 2024).
      </p>
      <p>
        Practitioners can compensate for the surveillance gap by triangulating
        several sources: adding gambling items to existing youth and adult
        health surveys; analyzing helpline call volume and NCPG helpline
        analytics for local patterns; reviewing the density and types of
        gambling access in the community (casinos, lottery retailers, and the
        explosion of mobile sports betting and online platforms); and
        gathering qualitative data through focus groups and key-informant
        interviews with treatment providers, schools, and cultural-community
        leaders. The prevention professional often has to <em>build</em> the
        gambling data picture rather than pull it off a shelf.
      </p>
      <p>
        Assessment also means understanding gambling-specific risk and
        protective factors. A systematic review of longitudinal studies
        identified the strongest early risk factors for later problem gambling
        as prior gambling-problem severity, male gender, and poor school
        performance, alongside alcohol use, antisocial behavior, depression,
        impulsivity, sensation-seeking, and the number of gambling activities
        engaged in; protective factors included parental supervision and
        higher socioeconomic status (Dowling et al., <em>Clinical Psychology
        Review</em>, 2017). Many of these — impulsivity, substance use, weak
        family and school connectedness — overlap with substance-use risk
        factors, which is one reason coordinated, multi-problem prevention is
        efficient.
      </p>

      <h3>Step 2 — Capacity</h3>
      <p>
        Capacity building answers <em>"What do you have to work with?"</em> —
        mobilizing the resources, partnerships, and readiness needed to
        address the prioritized need (SAMHSA, PEP19-01, 2019). It includes
        raising awareness, engaging stakeholders, building staff and coalition
        skills, and securing funding and infrastructure to sustain the work.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The gambling application — different partners at the table.</strong>
        Capacity for gambling prevention means recruiting partners a
        substance-only coalition may not yet have: state problem-gambling
        programs and the state's behavioral-health/prevention authority; NCPG
        and its network of state affiliates; gambling treatment providers and
        clinicians credentialed in gambling disorder; lottery agencies and
        gaming/sports-betting regulators (who often hold both data and
        dedicated PG funding streams); schools, athletics programs, and
        colleges, because youth, young adults, and athletes are higher-risk
        audiences; and trusted leaders in communities of color, which NCPG
        notes are often disproportionately affected by gambling harms (NCPG,
        Agility Grants, 2026).
      </p>
      <p>
        Capacity in gambling is also workforce development. Many prevention
        specialists were trained almost entirely on substances and need
        gambling-specific knowledge — what gambling disorder is, how it
        presents, how it overlaps with substance use disorders, and which
        interventions exist. EDC's SPF-for-gambling workshop is pitched
        explicitly at state and community substance-misuse practitioners and
        public-health professionals crossing into gambling (EDC, 2026).
        Funding capacity deserves candor too: gambling prevention has
        historically been under-resourced relative to substance prevention,
        and NCPG itself notes it receives no federal or dedicated state-level
        funding for its work (NCPG, NGAGE 3.0, 2024). National funders are
        beginning to fill the gap — NCPG's Agility Grants, supported by the
        NFL Foundation, granted more than $1 million from 2022 to 2024 and
        committed another $1.5 million for 2025–2027 (NCPG, Agility Grants,
        2026) — but diversifying funding remains a real capacity task.
      </p>

      <h3>Step 3 — Planning</h3>
      <p>
        Planning answers <em>"What should you do, and how should you do
        it?"</em> The SPF calls for a comprehensive, logic-model-driven
        strategic plan that connects the prioritized risk and protective
        factors to specific evidence-based interventions and measurable
        outcomes (SAMHSA, PEP19-01, 2019). A logic model makes the theory of
        change explicit: <em>these</em> local conditions and risk/protective
        factors lead us to select <em>these</em> strategies, which should
        produce <em>these</em> short- and long-term outcomes.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The gambling application — a gambling-specific logic model.</strong>
        Imagine a coalition that found high rates of adolescent sports betting
        and a community belief that "gambling is a good way to make money"
        (an NGAGE-identified risk predictor). A gambling-specific logic model
        would link those conditions to strategies such as youth education
        that corrects gambling-related cognitive distortions, family
        programming that strengthens parental supervision (a documented
        protective factor), and environmental and policy work on advertising
        exposure and age verification (NCPG, NGAGE 3.0, 2024; Dowling et al.,
        2017). Effective planning also matches the intervention to the right
        point on the Institute of Medicine continuum — universal education for
        a whole student body, selective programming for higher-risk groups
        such as athletes, indicated approaches for those already showing
        early signs.
      </p>
      <p>
        Planning is comprehensive when it combines individual-, relationship-,
        community-, and environmental-level strategies rather than relying on
        a single classroom curriculum. The sibling page on <a
        href="/understand-prevention/strategies">CSAP's six prevention
        strategies</a> details the intervention menu; the <a
        href="/understand-prevention/coalitions">Coalitions</a> page covers
        the seven CADCA strategies coalitions use to move community-level
        conditions. The planning step matches those menus to the gambling
        problem the data revealed.
      </p>

      <h3>Step 4 — Implementation</h3>
      <p>
        Implementation answers <em>"How do you put the plan into action?"</em>
        — delivering the selected evidence-based programs, practices, and
        policies, and doing so with <strong>fidelity</strong> to the model
        that made them effective, while making only carefully considered
        adaptations for local fit (SAMHSA, PEP19-01, 2019).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The gambling application — and the honest limit on the
        evidence.</strong> The SPF's instruction to implement evidence-based
        programs with fidelity assumes a well-stocked shelf of proven
        programs. For substances, that shelf is deep. For gambling, it is
        thinner and younger. Systematic reviews of educational
        gambling-prevention programs for adolescents find that many improve
        gambling knowledge and correct misconceptions, but evidence of durable
        change in gambling <em>behavior</em> is more limited and the research
        base is still developing (Keen, Blaszczynski &amp; Anjoul, 2017;
        adolescent and young-adult gambling-prevention reviews). The practical
        implication is twofold. First, select the best-evidenced gambling
        programs available and run them with fidelity; where adaptation is
        unavoidable, document it and monitor whether it preserves the active
        ingredients. Second, because the gambling-specific evidence base is
        still maturing, implementation and evaluation are tightly linked —
        programs implemented today are often also contributing to the
        evidence base, which is why funders like NCPG fund prevention
        innovation and require evaluation as a condition of their grants
        (NCPG, Agility Grants, 2026).
      </p>

      <h3>Step 5 — Evaluation</h3>
      <p>
        Evaluation answers <em>"Is your plan succeeding?"</em> — examining
        both <em>process</em> (was the program delivered as intended, to the
        intended audience, with fidelity?) and <em>outcome</em> (did the
        targeted risk/protective factors and behaviors move?). In the SPF,
        evaluation is not a final report card; it feeds back into the cycle
        to refine assessment, capacity, and planning (SAMHSA, PEP19-01,
        2019). The KU Center frames evaluation as ideally <em>participatory</em>
        — used to shape the initiative over time, not just to render a
        one-time summative judgment (KU Center for Community Health &amp;
        Development, Community Tool Box, 1994–2025).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>The gambling application — measuring gambling-specific
        outcomes.</strong> Gambling evaluation should measure gambling-specific
        indicators rather than borrowing substance metrics. Process measures
        track reach and fidelity — how many youth, athletes, or families
        were reached; whether the curriculum was delivered completely.
        Outcome measures should track gambling-specific constructs: changes
        in gambling knowledge and in cognitive distortions (e.g., the belief
        that gambling is a reliable way to make money), changes in attitudes
        and intentions, changes in protective factors such as perceived
        parental supervision, and — where feasible and using validated
        instruments — changes in gambling behavior and early problem
        indicators. The challenge mirrors the assessment-stage data gap:
        because routine gambling surveillance is sparse, evaluators often
        must build their own pre/post measures using validated screens and
        survey items. National funders increasingly treat evaluation capacity
        as essential — NCPG offers Agility Grant applicants program-evaluation
        coaching and a "Basics of Program Evaluation" webinar, and requires
        recipients to submit a final impact report with activity, demographic,
        and outcome data (NCPG, Agility Grants, 2026).
      </p>

      <h2>The two cross-cutting principles</h2>
      <p>
        The SPF embeds two guiding principles in every step rather than
        treating them as separate stages: cultural competence and
        sustainability (SAMHSA, SPTAC, n.d.).
      </p>

      <h3>Cultural competence</h3>
      <p>
        Cultural competence means designing and delivering prevention in ways
        that fit the language, values, and lived experience of the specific
        populations being served — and involving those communities in
        assessment, planning, implementation, and evaluation. In gambling
        prevention this is not optional polish. NCPG notes that gambling
        harms are often more prevalent in historically underrepresented
        communities and that Black, Hispanic, Native American, Asian, and
        other communities of color are among the populations at higher risk;
        it explicitly prioritizes amplifying the voices and leadership of
        people from those communities (NCPG, Agility Grants, 2026). Cultural
        communities also have distinct gambling norms, games, and meanings,
        so a program that works in one setting may need genuine adaptation —
        not just translation — to work in another.
      </p>

      <h3>Sustainability</h3>
      <p>
        Sustainability means planning from the outset to keep effective
        prevention going beyond any single grant cycle — diversifying
        funding, institutionalizing programs within schools and community
        organizations, and maintaining partnerships and trained staff. The
        SPF treats sustainability as something to build into capacity and
        planning early, not to scramble for at the end. CADCA's coalition
        examples illustrate the principle: the Steuben Prevention Coalition
        bridged a gap year of lost federal funding by securing replacement
        support from county and partner sources, then leveraged those
        partnerships into new programming (CADCA, Coalitions in Action,
        2020). For gambling prevention, sustainability is especially pressing
        because dedicated, stable funding has historically been scarce;
        building diversified support (state PG funds, gaming-revenue
        set-asides where they exist, national grants, and institutional
        ownership by schools and health systems) is part of the prevention
        task itself.
      </p>

      <h2>The honest state of the evidence</h2>
      <p>
        Two claims are easy to conflate, and worth keeping separate. The
        first — that the SPF <em>planning process</em> is sound and applicable
        to gambling — is well-supported: the SPF is a validated, widely used,
        data-driven framework, and national gambling-prevention funders and
        trainers have formally adopted it (SAMHSA, PEP19-01, 2019; NCPG,
        Agility Grants, 2026; EDC, 2026). The second claim — that any given
        gambling prevention <em>program</em> is proven to reduce gambling
        harm — has to be made more cautiously. The gambling-specific
        risk-and-protective-factor evidence is reasonably strong and
        increasingly clear (Dowling et al., 2017), but the program-effectiveness
        base is younger and thinner than the substance base, with the
        clearest effects on knowledge and attitudes and less settled evidence
        on durable behavior change. The responsible posture for practitioners
        is to use the SPF with confidence as the planning engine, select the
        best-evidenced gambling interventions available, implement with
        fidelity, and evaluate rigorously — because today's well-evaluated
        gambling prevention work is helping build the evidence base the field
        still needs.
      </p>

      <h2>How this connects to the rest of the toolkit</h2>
      <p>
        The SPF is the organizing spine of modern prevention practice; the
        sibling pages in this section show what gets plugged into it. The
        page on <a href="/understand-prevention/strategies">CSAP's six
        prevention strategies</a> details the intervention menu used in
        Planning and Implementation. The page on <a
        href="/understand-prevention/coalitions">Coalitions</a> develops the
        partnership and capacity work that powers Step 2. The page on <a
        href="/understand-prevention/comorbidities">co-occurring conditions</a>
        explains why gambling, substance use, and mental-health problems
        share risk and protective factors — and why assessment and planning
        that address them together are more efficient than siloed efforts.
        Read alongside those pages, the SPF is less a five-box diagram and
        more a repeatable way of thinking that turns local gambling data into
        effective, sustainable, culturally grounded prevention.
      </p>

